    {
      "id": "Cdqnaoj1FBJHJ40v359Rv",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 210.7913159199752,
      "y": -1988.0923841864928,
      "width": 1434.1666259765625,
      "height": 3475,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bCe",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 687716412,
      "version": 9953,
      "versionNonce": 1797757372,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "l8p0Joy_yS2yyJsyQ1VBH",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1772846989916,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Google/Quip Documents\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n    1. Users should be able to create new documents\n    2. Multiple users (limit 100) should be able to edit the documents concurrently.\n    3. Users should be able to view each other changes in real-time\n    4. Users should be able to see the cursor position and presence of each other. \n\nScale - \n    1. 10M concurrent users with a max TPS of 10M/sec.\n    2. 1 Billion documents\n\nNon-Functional requirements - \n   1. The system should be highly available and should be eventually consistent. \n   2. Users should be able to create documents within 300-500ms.\n   3. Users should be able to edit their documents within 300-500ms\n   4. Viewing each other changes should be in real-time within 100ms\n   5. Viewing other presence using cursor position should be within 100ms\n   6. The system should be fault-tolerant and should not loose any data.\n\n\nAPI Routes - \n\n1. POST /document/ --> status code 200 and documentId\n\n{\n    title\n    authorId\n    timestamp\n    ...metadata\n}\n\n2. POST /document/<documentId>/location/<locationId> --> edit documents\n\n{\n    text\n    timestamp\n    userId\n}\n\n3. GET /document/<documentId>/location/<locationId> --> view changes\n\n{\n   text\n   timestamp\n   userId\n}\n\n4. GET /document/<documentId>/cursors --> retrieve all available cursors of users editing the doc\n\n{\n    cursorId\n    location: \n    userId\n    timestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design - \n\n1. How will users be able to create new documents?\n     a. Browser makes a POST request to CREATE microservice which makes the metadata entry in DOCUMENT table\n     b. Microservice generates a blank HTML page and returns to the browser.\n\n2. How can we extend the design so that multiple users can edit the same document concurrently \n(especially when they are making changes simultaneously)?\n\nScenario 1: \n     a. If users are making changes at different positions in the same document\n     b. Say both User1 and User2 got hold of the cursors at different location and they typed \"a\" and \"c\" concurrently.\n     c. Firstly, client-side logic in Browser will apply operational transform such as \"INSERT(\"a\", location)\" and INSERT(\"b\", location)\n        and then they will upload the changes to EDIT microservice.\n     d. Since EDIT microservice receives 2 changes at the same timestamp but at different location, there is no conflict to resolve.\n     e. It simply performs Operational Transform and persist the changes in the Write Ahead Log.\n     f. We will have a periodic snapshot which will prepare the document from WAL and then persist the changes in S3 (for recovery)\n     g. Once the server-side persistence is complete, it will publish the operation transform to the Pub/Sub so that it gets broadcasted\n          to all the users. Topic is the documentId\n     h. Both User1 and User2 will be connected to Edit microservice for bi-directional communication (via websocket) and if they are\n         different instances, both of them will be subscribed to the topic. So, if EDIT microservice instance successfully writes to WAL,\n         it will publish to Pub/Sub which will go to the another EDIT microservice instance connecting User2 and will provide User1\n         changes. Similarly, User1 will receive User2 changes\n      i. LOCAL WAL is a database of client side editor to apply the changes locally.\n\nScenario 2:\n    a. If users are making changes at the same position in the same document.\n    b. Similar to above workflow, but it will require a conflict resolution management where EDIT microservice will redirect the \n        Operation Transform generated from client side to the a single server handling the specific document ID.\n    c. The Conflict Resolution Server will be sharded by documentID such that for the same position of the same document, it \n        can apply operation transform and then directly write to WAL and write to the topic (documentId) so that all the instances\n        of EDIT microservice can receive the Operational Transform (conflict resolved) and then return to the respective users.\n\nIn Scenario 1, we never needed the conflict resolution and in that case EDIT microservice would take the lead on writing to WAL and \nthen publishing the changes to Pub/Sub.\n\nHowever, Scenario 2 bought the conflict resolution server and I believe, we should use for Scenario 1 also because if users are connected\nto different instances of the EDIT microservice, we won't be able to know whether it is Scenario 1 or Scenario2.\n\nSo, the updated architecture - \n    1. All EDIT calls to the microservice gets redirected to Conflict Resolution Server, sharded by document ID.\n    2. For similar timestamp, the Conflict Resolution Server will resolve based on last modified timestamp and apply Operational Transform\n    3. Write the OT to WAL and then proceed to write it to Pub/Sub for the topicID = documentId\n    4. All different instances of EDIT microservice would receive the updated OT and look in-memory to find <Topic>:{WebSocket1, WS2} and \n        then return the resolved OT to WS1 (user1) and WS2 (user2)\n    5. The client-side editor will apply those changes locally and persist them in Local WAL.\n\n\n3. How will users be able to view each other's changes in real-time?\n    a. All calls from EDIT microservice --> Conflict Resolution Servicer --> resolves conflicts --> Writes to WAL --> Writes to Topic (documentId)\n    b. All different instances are subscribed to Pub/Sub --> receives resolved OTs --> Look at in-memory of <Topic>:{WebSocket1, WS2}\n    c. Send the resolved OTs to the users --> Then apply OT locally \n\n\n4. How can we enable users to see the cursor position and presence (whether they're connected or not) of other users?\n      a. USER1 and USER2 makes POST request to EDIT microservice which receives the location that the user is editing.\n      b. Since cursor changes are transient and it is not used to make any business decisions, we don't need to persist them.\n      c. We can persist them in memory if the user connected and then fire a presence/cursor event to the pub/sub which gets directed to \n          other users via web socket connection.\n      d. when a user drops off, it should publish a 'user disconnected' presence event to Pub/Sub, which broadcasts the updated presence status \n          to all other users viewing that document\n\n\n5. How do we scale to millions of connections from our users?\n     1. CREATE/EDIT microservice can horizontally scale as they are stateless\n     2. DB metadata can be shared by DocumentId\n     3. WAL can be sharded by DocumentId\n     4. Pub/Sub can be sharded by DocumentId\n     5. Conflict Resolution Server needs to be shareded by DocumentId so that all calls to EDIT microservice for the same\n         documentId can hit the 1 Conflict Resolution Server instance to resolve conflicts.\n\n\n6. How can we optimize document storage?\n    1. We are using Snapshot service which would be responsible for re-creating the document and persisting in S3 so that we can delete operations from WAL.\n          a. We would create a new WAL and redirect new OTs to the new WAL.\n          b. Snapshot service will query the existing WAL to prepare the document and persist in S3 and then delete the WAL.\n          c. Rename the new WAL to the existing WAL.\n    2. We can possibly do content-based chunking where we store chunks of the document in S3 and persist the chunk metadata in our architecture \n         and for chunks whose content hash is same, we would avoid persisting them again and use the same S3 URL in the chunk metadata\n   \n     \n     ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Google/Quip Documents\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n    1. Users should be able to create new documents\n    2. Multiple users (limit 100) should be able to edit the documents concurrently.\n    3. Users should be able to view each other changes in real-time\n    4. Users should be able to see the cursor position and presence of each other. \n\nScale - \n    1. 10M concurrent users with a max TPS of 10M/sec.\n    2. 1 Billion documents\n\nNon-Functional requirements - \n   1. The system should be highly available and should be eventually consistent. \n   2. Users should be able to create documents within 300-500ms.\n   3. Users should be able to edit their documents within 300-500ms\n   4. Viewing each other changes should be in real-time within 100ms\n   5. Viewing other presence using cursor position should be within 100ms\n   6. The system should be fault-tolerant and should not loose any data.\n\n\nAPI Routes - \n\n1. POST /document/ --> status code 200 and documentId\n\n{\n    title\n    authorId\n    timestamp\n    ...metadata\n}\n\n2. POST /document/<documentId>/location/<locationId> --> edit documents\n\n{\n    text\n    timestamp\n    userId\n}\n\n3. GET /document/<documentId>/location/<locationId> --> view changes\n\n{\n   text\n   timestamp\n   userId\n}\n\n4. GET /document/<documentId>/cursors --> retrieve all available cursors of users editing the doc\n\n{\n    cursorId\n    location: \n    userId\n    timestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design - \n\n1. How will users be able to create new documents?\n     a. Browser makes a POST request to CREATE microservice which makes the metadata entry in DOCUMENT table\n     b. Microservice generates a blank HTML page and returns to the browser.\n\n2. How can we extend the design so that multiple users can edit the same document concurrently \n(especially when they are making changes simultaneously)?\n\nScenario 1: \n     a. If users are making changes at different positions in the same document\n     b. Say both User1 and User2 got hold of the cursors at different location and they typed \"a\" and \"c\" concurrently.\n     c. Firstly, client-side logic in Browser will apply operational transform such as \"INSERT(\"a\", location)\" and INSERT(\"b\", location)\n        and then they will upload the changes to EDIT microservice.\n     d. Since EDIT microservice receives 2 changes at the same timestamp but at different location, there is no conflict to resolve.\n     e. It simply performs Operational Transform and persist the changes in the Write Ahead Log.\n     f. We will have a periodic snapshot which will prepare the document from WAL and then persist the changes in S3 (for recovery)\n     g. Once the server-side persistence is complete, it will publish the operation transform to the Pub/Sub so that it gets broadcasted\n          to all the users. Topic is the documentId\n     h. Both User1 and User2 will be connected to Edit microservice for bi-directional communication (via websocket) and if they are\n         different instances, both of them will be subscribed to the topic. So, if EDIT microservice instance successfully writes to WAL,\n         it will publish to Pub/Sub which will go to the another EDIT microservice instance connecting User2 and will provide User1\n         changes. Similarly, User1 will receive User2 changes\n      i. LOCAL WAL is a database of client side editor to apply the changes locally.\n\nScenario 2:\n    a. If users are making changes at the same position in the same document.\n    b. Similar to above workflow, but it will require a conflict resolution management where EDIT microservice will redirect the \n        Operation Transform generated from client side to the a single server handling the specific document ID.\n    c. The Conflict Resolution Server will be sharded by documentID such that for the same position of the same document, it \n        can apply operation transform and then directly write to WAL and write to the topic (documentId) so that all the instances\n        of EDIT microservice can receive the Operational Transform (conflict resolved) and then return to the respective users.\n\nIn Scenario 1, we never needed the conflict resolution and in that case EDIT microservice would take the lead on writing to WAL and \nthen publishing the changes to Pub/Sub.\n\nHowever, Scenario 2 bought the conflict resolution server and I believe, we should use for Scenario 1 also because if users are connected\nto different instances of the EDIT microservice, we won't be able to know whether it is Scenario 1 or Scenario2.\n\nSo, the updated architecture - \n    1. All EDIT calls to the microservice gets redirected to Conflict Resolution Server, sharded by document ID.\n    2. For similar timestamp, the Conflict Resolution Server will resolve based on last modified timestamp and apply Operational Transform\n    3. Write the OT to WAL and then proceed to write it to Pub/Sub for the topicID = documentId\n    4. All different instances of EDIT microservice would receive the updated OT and look in-memory to find <Topic>:{WebSocket1, WS2} and \n        then return the resolved OT to WS1 (user1) and WS2 (user2)\n    5. The client-side editor will apply those changes locally and persist them in Local WAL.\n\n\n3. How will users be able to view each other's changes in real-time?\n    a. All calls from EDIT microservice --> Conflict Resolution Servicer --> resolves conflicts --> Writes to WAL --> Writes to Topic (documentId)\n    b. All different instances are subscribed to Pub/Sub --> receives resolved OTs --> Look at in-memory of <Topic>:{WebSocket1, WS2}\n    c. Send the resolved OTs to the users --> Then apply OT locally \n\n\n4. How can we enable users to see the cursor position and presence (whether they're connected or not) of other users?\n      a. USER1 and USER2 makes POST request to EDIT microservice which receives the location that the user is editing.\n      b. Since cursor changes are transient and it is not used to make any business decisions, we don't need to persist them.\n      c. We can persist them in memory if the user connected and then fire a presence/cursor event to the pub/sub which gets directed to \n          other users via web socket connection.\n      d. when a user drops off, it should publish a 'user disconnected' presence event to Pub/Sub, which broadcasts the updated presence status \n          to all other users viewing that document\n\n\n5. How do we scale to millions of connections from our users?\n     1. CREATE/EDIT microservice can horizontally scale as they are stateless\n     2. DB metadata can be shared by DocumentId\n     3. WAL can be sharded by DocumentId\n     4. Pub/Sub can be sharded by DocumentId\n     5. Conflict Resolution Server needs to be shareded by DocumentId so that all calls to EDIT microservice for the same\n         documentId can hit the 1 Conflict Resolution Server instance to resolve conflicts.\n\n\n6. How can we optimize document storage?\n    1. We are using Snapshot service which would be responsible for re-creating the document and persisting in S3 so that we can delete operations from WAL.\n          a. We would create a new WAL and redirect new OTs to the new WAL.\n          b. Snapshot service will query the existing WAL to prepare the document and persist in S3 and then delete the WAL.\n          c. Rename the new WAL to the existing WAL.\n    2. We can possibly do content-based chunking where we store chunks of the document in S3 and persist the chunk metadata in our architecture \n         and for chunks whose content hash is same, we would avoid persisting them again and use the same S3 URL in the chunk metadata\n   \n     \n     ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
